    <stitle>10 SPEED TRANSMISSIONS SPICER - REMOVE - OPTIONAL RANGE CASE</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc id="hl1302301" svcproctype="remove" graphiccount="8">
        <title>OPTIONAL RANGE CASE</title>
        <svcsubproc id="hl1302302">
            <title>Procedure for Conventional Vehicles</title>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>It is possible to service the range case without removing the entire transmission from the
                        vehicle.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>Turn off and bleed the air system to prevent air lines from whipping, which could cause
                        injury.
                    </para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Begin by removing the electric speedometer sensor and 1/4 inch air lines (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1302333">Figure 33</hotlnk>). Remove the end yoke or flange.
                </para>
                <figure id="f1302333" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1302333" filename="../figg13/g1302333.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 33. Optional Range Case - Remove End Yoke</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">A range case support fixture (ZTSE4278) and a transmission jack stand will be needed (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1302334">Figure 34</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f1302334" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1302334" filename="../figg13/g1302334.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 34. Support Fixture</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove all range case bolts except one at the top of the case (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1302335">Figure 35</hotlnk>). Then secure the bracket to the output shaft using the
                    output washer and nut. Tighten the nut to 550 to 600 ft-lbs. (745 to 813 N&#8226;m). Use pry bars in
                    the milled slots to help break the seal between case sections.
                </para>
                <figure id="f1302335" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1302335" filename="../figg13/g1302335.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 35. Remove Range Case Bolts</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Detach the range section from the rest of the unit (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1302336">Figure 36</hotlnk>). Pull the range section straight off. It must be level
                    with the rest of the unit.
                </para>
                <figure id="f1302336" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1302336" filename="../figg13/g1302336.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 36. Detach Range Section</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">These parts can be serviced without removing the entire transmission completely from the
                    vehicle (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1302337">Figure 37</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f1302337" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1302337" filename="../figg13/g1302337.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 37. Service Without Removing</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc id="hl1302303">
            <title>Procedure for Cabover Vehicles</title>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>It is possible to service the range case without removing the entire transmission from the
                        vehicle.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove all range case bolts except one at the top of the case (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1302338">Figure 38</hotlnk>). Also remove the 1/4 inch air lines. Then install a
                    lift hook and hoist to the range section.
                </para>
                <figure id="f1302338" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1302338" filename="../figg13/g1302338.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 38. Cabover Vehicles - Range Case Removal</caption>
                </figure>
                <specpara>
                    <warning>
                        <para>When moving heavy parts, use a chain hoist to help prevent personal injury.</para>
                    </warning>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the final case bolt and pull the range section from the rest of the unit (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1302339">Figure 39</hotlnk>). A screwdriver or pry bars can be used in the case
                    slots to break the seal.
                </para>
                <figure id="f1302339" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1302339" filename="../figg13/g1302339.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 39. Remove Final Case Bolt</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">These parts can be serviced without removing the entire transmission completely from the
                    vehicle (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1302340">Figure 40</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f1302340" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1302340" filename="../figg13/g1302340.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 40. Service Without Removing Transmission</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
    </svcproc>
